{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181028090555|866109394","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Tom_O'Halleran","to":"Tom O'Halleran"}],"pages":{"13057371":{"pageid":13057371,"ns":0,"title":"Tom O'Halleran","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-28T09:06:32Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Tom O'Halleran\n|image         = Tom O'Halleran official portrait.jpg\n|state         = [[Arizona]]\n|district      = {{ushr|AZ|1|1st}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2017\n|term_end      =\n|predecessor   = [[Ann Kirkpatrick]]\n|successor     =\n|state_senate1 = Arizona\n|district1     = 1st\n|term_start1   = 2007\n|term_end1     = 2009\n|predecessor1  = [[Ken Bennett]]\n|successor1    = [[Steve Pierce]]\n|birth_name    = Thomas Charles O'Halleran\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1946|1|24}}\n|birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (2015\u2013present)\n|otherparty    = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2014\u20132015)<br>[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (Before 2014)\n|spouse        = Pat\n|education     = [[Lewis University]]<br>[[DePaul University]]\n|website       = {{url|ohalleran.house.gov|House website}}\n}} \n'''Thomas Charles O'Halleran'''  ({{IPAc-en|o\u028a|\u02c8|h|\u00e6|l|\u0259|r|\u0259|n}}; born January 24, 1946) is a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]], representing {{ushr|AZ|1}}. He began his political career as a Republican, but is now a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat.]]\n\n==Early career==\nO'Halleran served with the [[Chicago Police Department]] from 1966 to 1979.  He then became a member of the [[Chicago Board of Trade]], operating his own futures trading business.<ref name=bio>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tomohalleran.com/about-tom|title=Meet Tom - Tom O'Halleran for Congress |website=www.tomohalleran.com|accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Arizona Legislature==\nO'Halleran, then a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], served in the [[Arizona House of Representatives]] from 2001 to 2006. He then served in the [[Arizona Senate|Arizona State Senate]], representing the 1st District from 2007 to 2009. In a 2008 primary election, he was unseated by [[Steve Pierce]].\n\nAfter leaving the Arizona State Legislature, O'Halleran hosted a radio show on [[KAZM]] in [[Sedona, Arizona|Sedona]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bell|first1=David|title=Former state Rep. O'Halleran joins CD1 candidate field |url=http://www.eacourier.com/news/former-state-rep-o-halleran-joins-cd-candidate-field/article_f9153f5e-3af5-11e5-8da2-9b95e830e54c.html|accessdate=March 1, 2016|publisher=Eastern Arizona Courier|date=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 he left the Republican Party, citing its policies on education, water, and child welfare as reasons for his resignation. He then ran for the 6th District State Senate seat as an Independent, losing by 3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom O'Halleran|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Tom_O'Halleran|publisher=[[Ballotpedia]]|accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2016 campaign===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2016#District 1}}\nOn August 6, 2015, O'Halleran announced his candidacy as a Democrat for [[Arizona's 1st congressional district]].<ref>{{cite news|title=O\u2019Halleran announces candidacy in 1st Congressional District|url=http://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2015/08/05/ohalleran-announces-candidacy-in-1st-congressional-district/|accessdate=1 March 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Arizona Capitol Times|date=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe explained his switch of party affiliation as a result of his positive attitude toward government, and, in particular, of his support for government regulations that would increase the use of wind and solar energy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanders |first1=Rebekah L. |title=Tom O\u2019Halleran running for Congress as Democrat |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/arizona/politics/2015/08/04/tom-ohalleran-running-congress-democrat/31087643/ |website=azCentral |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, O'Halleran was named to the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]]'s Red to Blue list, indicating that his race was a priority for the group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dccc.org/red-blue/|title=Red to Blue - DCCC|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2016, O'Halleran beat Miguel Olivas in the Democratic primary.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reagan|first1=Kevin|title=Bennett joins Babeu in pledging to term limits|url=http://www.trivalleycentral.com/arizona_city_independent/news/bennett-joins-babeu-in-pledging-to-term-limits/article_529226b2-58d9-11e6-80e8-bf1ef634e93e.html|accessdate=9 August 2016|publisher=Arizona City Independent|date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> He faced Republican [[Paul Babeu]] and Green Party candidate Ray Parrish<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2016.azvoterguide.com/candidates/2016/federal/us-house-of-representatives/ray-parrish/|title=Ray Parrish {{!}} azvoterguide.com|website=2016.azvoterguide.com|access-date=2016-09-24}}</ref> in the general election on November 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kjzz.org/content/358303/its-republican-paul-babeu-and-democrat-tom-ohalleran-monstrous-cd-1-race|title=It's Republican Paul Babeu And Democrat Tom O'Halleran In Monstrous CD-1 Race|date=31 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> O'Halleran won, receiving 51% of the vote to Babeu's 44%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Democrat Tom O'Halleran defeats Pinal County Sheriff Paul Babeu in CD-1|url=http://www.abc15.com/news/state/democrat-tom-ohalleran-defeats-pinal-county-sheriff-paul-babeu-in-cd-1|accessdate=11 November 2016|publisher=ABC 15|date=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Blue Dog Coalition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://bluedogcaucus-costa.house.gov/members|publisher=Blue dog coalition|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 campaign===\nIn May 2017, Republican State Senator [[Steve Smith (Arizona politician)|Steve Smith]] of Maricopa announced that he was running for O'Halloran's seat. Smith, who had the support of GOP Congressmen [[Trent Franks]] and [[Andy Biggs]], was described by an local news operation in Arizona as \u201can immigration hard-liner who championed the idea of paying for a border wall with private donations.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Resnik |first1=Brahm |title=GOP lawmaker running for Congress in northern Arizona district |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/politics/gop-lawmaker-running-for-congress-in-northern-arizona-district/75-439841907 |website=12News |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Commodity Exchanges, Energy, and Credit|Subcommittee on Commodity Exchanges, Energy, and Credit]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Tenure==\n===Political issues===\n====Government spending====\nIn March 2018, O'Halleran criticized the Trump Administration for seeking to cut funding for such agencies and programs as the [[Economic Development Administration]], the Rural Business and Cooperative Service, the Manufacturing Extension Partnership, Community Development Block Grants, Rural Water and Wastewater Grants, Indian Community Development Block Grant, the Rural Economic Development Program, [[Essential Air Service]], and Native American Housing Block Grants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Singleton |first1=Laura |title=O\u2019Halleran concerned about rural programs on the Trump administration's chopping block |url=http://www.wmicentral.com/news/latest_news/o-halleran-concerned-about-rural-programs-on-the-trump-administration/article_5a81afdc-c2b5-5bae-a66e-7abb1a930779.html |website=White Mountain Independent |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Gun control====\nAfter the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in Parkland, Florida, O'Halleran, who had long supported expanded background checks but opposed an assault-weapon ban, suggested he might shift toward a stronger position on gun control. \u201cAt times you have to look at yourself in the mirror and do the right thing and say forget about the political consequences,\u201d he said, but admitted he was concerned about those consequences.<ref>{{cite web |last1=BADE |first1=RACHAEL |last2=EVERETT |first2=Burgess |title=Could gun control flip the House to Democrats? |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/01/guns-midterms-congress-republicans-democrats-430779 |website=Politico |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nIn March 2017, O'Halleran denounced the Republican health-care replacement plan, saying that it would fail \u201cto provide affordable access to health coverage,\u201d would disproportionately affect rural communities, force seniors to pay higher premiums, and give CEOs \"a tax break on the backs of hardworking Arizona families.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=REP. O\u2019HALLERAN DENOUNCES HEALTH CARE REPLACEMENT |url=https://ohalleran.house.gov/newsroom/press-releases/rep-o-halleran-denounces-health-care-replacement |website=ohalleran.house.gov |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nWhen President [[Donald Trump]] ordered a [[Executive Order 13769|travel ban]] on visitors and refugees from seven predominantly Muslim nations in January 2017, O'Halleran said that the order \u201cdoes not represent our nation's values\u201d and that it violated the Constitution and \"the bedrock ideals of our democracy.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=FARZAN |first1=ANTONIA NOORI |title=Here's Where Arizona's Top Elected Officials Stand on Trump's Border Wall |url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/heres-which-arizona-politicians-support-the-border-wall-and-which-ones-oppose-it-9274495 |website=Phoenix New Times |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, O'Halleran criticized Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]]'s tougher new guidelines on expelling illegal immigrants who belong to criminal gangs. \u201cI have no problem with getting the felons out of the country,\u201d O'Halleran said. \"But some of these people that they're taking out of the country, they have children that are Americans, and they have not had a violent felony conviction. Here we are, taking mothers away from their children.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nintzel |first1=Jim |title=Congressman Raul Grijalva sues Trump administration over border wall plans |url=https://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/the-skinny/Content?oid=8528615 |website=The Skinny - Tucson Weekly |accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nO'Halleran was part of a group of Arizona Democrats who, in an August 2017 letter to President Trump, urged him not to pardon former [[Maricopa County]] chief Sheriff [[Joe Arpaio]], who had been convicted in a federal court of racially profiling Latinos as part of border patrols.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Jim |title=Arizona members of US Congress ask president not to pardon Arpaio |url=http://ktar.com/story/1697848/arizona-members-of-us-congress-ask-president-not-to-pardon-arpaio/ |website=KTAR News |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> \"It is imperative for a society to hold elected leaders to the highest level of accountability, and when they are convicted of crimes and lose the trust of the public, they must face their punishment,\u201d said O'Halleran. \u201cAs a former law enforcement officer, Joe Arpaio's abuse and exploitation of his power to target vulnerable communities is beyond egregious and tarnishes the sworn duty of our brave officers across Arizona.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Arizona Congressmen to Trump: Don\u2019t Pardon Joe Arpaio |url=https://rubengallego.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/arizona-congressmen-trump-don-t-pardon-joe-arpaio |website=rubengallego.house.gov |accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=HANSEN |first1=RONALD J. |last2=WINGETT SANCHEZ |first2=YVONNE |title=Some in Arizona who sought Joe Arpaio's support mum on possible pardon |url=https://amp.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2017/08/25/joe-arpaio-criminal-contempt-donald-trump-pardon-arizona-politicians-doug-ducey-mum-support-oppose/594843001/ |website=The Republic - az Central |accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Halleran and his wife, Pat, live in unincorporated [[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai County]] (with a Sedona address), and have three grown children and four grandchildren.<ref name=bio/><ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/olm-115.pdf Official list of congressmen] for 115th Congress, on which O'Halleran is listed as \"D-Sedona\")</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [https://ohalleran.house.gov Congressman Tom O'Halleran] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.tomohalleran.com Campaign website]\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = O000171 | fec = H6AZ01199 | congress = tom-o-halleran/O000171 | votesmart = 28499 }}\n* [https://www.opensecrets.org/races/election.php?state=AZ OpenSecrets.org]\n* {{C-SPAN|tomohalleran}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-az-sen}}\n{{succession box|title=Member of the [[Arizona Senate]] for the 1st District|before=[[Ken Bennett]]|after=[[Steve Pierce]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ann Kirkpatrick]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Arizona|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Arizona's 1st congressional district]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephanie Murphy]]<br>D-[[Florida]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=408th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jimmy Panetta]]<br>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AZ-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 115th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Arizona]]}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ohalleran, Tom}}\n[[Category:Arizona state senators]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona Democrats]]\n[[Category:Arizona Republicans]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Members of the Arizona House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United Sta